## Wire Fetch, Then Use

Sketch that fetches data from a URL, stores it, reads it back, and extracts a field:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (four steps)
(define response (fetch \"https://api.example.com/status\"))
(store :api-cache response)
(define cached (loam/recall :api-cache))
(cdr (assoc 'status cached))
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(cdr (assoc 'status 
            (loam/recall :api-cache 
                         :from (store :api-cache 
                                      (fetch \"https://api.example.com/status\")))))
```

*[needs: fetch, store, loam/recall with :from]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire fetch + store + loam retrieval with inline store -->

The fetch closes the store, the store closes the recall, the recall closes the `assoc`, the `assoc` closes the `cdr`. One wire-shot. No `response`. No `cached`. No gap where staleness can enter.

---

## Conditional Fetch

Sketch that checks a cache, and only fetches if the cache is empty:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (three steps)
(define cached (loam/recall :weather-data))
(define data (if cached cached (fetch \"https://weather.example.com/now\")))
(cdr (assoc 'temp data))
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(cdr (assoc 'temp 
            (or (loam/recall :weather-data) 
                (fetch \"https://weather.example.com/now\"))))
```

*[needs: loam/recall, fetch]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire loam recall + fetch -->

The `or` short-circuits. If the recall succeeds, the fetch never happens. If the recall returns `#f`, the fetch runs and closes the `or`. One form.

---

## Knowledge Lookup, Then Format

Sketch that looks up a category in world knowledge, checks if it's empty, and formats a response:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (three steps)
(define facts (knowledge/of :category \"owls\"))
(define summary (if facts (car facts) \"No data available.\"))
(string-append \"Fact: \" summary)
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(string-append \"Fact: \" 
               (if (knowledge/of :category \"owls\") 
                   (car (knowledge/of :category \"owls\")) 
                   \"No data available.\"))
```

*[needs: knowledge/of]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire knowledge surface -->

Wait—this calls `knowledge/of` twice. We can do better with a `let` that still closes in one form:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT (let for single lookup)
(let ((facts (knowledge/of :category \"owls\")))
  (string-append \"Fact: \" 
                 (if facts (car facts) \"No data available.\")))
```

*[needs: knowledge/of]*

The `let` is part of the one-shot. The binding lives only for the body. No top-level `define`.

---

## Registry Check, Then Action

Sketch that checks if a capability is available, then acts on it:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (three steps)
(define can-speak (system/registry :domain \"voice\"))
(define action (if can-speak \"Speaking now.\" \"Voice unavailable.\"))
action
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(if (system/registry :domain \"voice\") 
    \"Speaking now.\" 
    \"Voice unavailable.\")
```

*[needs: system/registry]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire registry surface -->

The registry check *is* the conditional. No `can-speak`. The guard and the work are one expression.

