## Wire Fetch With Fallback

Sketch that tries two URLs, falling back to the second if the first fails:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (three steps)
(define primary (fetch \"https://api.example.com/primary\"))
(define data (if primary primary (fetch \"https://api.example.com/fallback\")))
(cdr (assoc 'value data))
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(cdr (assoc 'value 
            (or (fetch \"https://api.example.com/primary\") 
                (fetch \"https://api.example.com/fallback\"))))
```

*[needs: fetch with #f on failure]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire fetch to return #f on HTTP error -->

The `or` short-circuits. If the primary succeeds, the fallback never runs. If the primary fails (returning `#f`), the fallback runs and closes the `or`. One form.

---

## Knowledge + World in One

Sketch that checks local knowledge, then queries world knowledge if local is empty:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (three steps)
(define local (knowledge/of :category \"penguins\"))
(define answer (if local (car local) (world/knowledge :query \"penguin habitat\")))
(string-append \"Answer: \" answer)
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(string-append \"Answer: \" 
               (or (let ((local (knowledge/of :category \"penguins\"))) 
                     (and local (car local))) 
                   (world/knowledge :query \"penguin habitat\")))
```

*[needs: knowledge/of, world/knowledge]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire knowledge + world surfaces -->

The `let` checks local knowledge. The `and` guards the `car`. If local is empty, the `or` falls through to the world query. One form.

---

## Nested Wire-Shots

Sketch that fetches user profile, then fetches preferences based on a field in the profile:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (four steps)
(define profile (fetch \"https://api.example.com/user/profile\"))
(define user-id (cdr (assoc 'id profile)))
(define prefs-url (string-append \"https://api.example.com/user/\" user-id \"/prefs\"))
(fetch prefs-url)
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(fetch (string-append \"https://api.example.com/user/\" 
                      (cdr (assoc 'id 
                                  (fetch \"https://api.example.com/user/profile\"))) 
                      \"/prefs\"))
```

*[needs: fetch]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire fetch -->

The inner fetch closes inside the `assoc`, which closes inside the `cdr`, which closes inside the `string-append`, which closes inside the outer fetch. Two wire-shots, one top-level form. No `profile`. No `user-id`. No `prefs-url`.

