## Knowledge + Recall + Fallback Chain

Sketch that tries local knowledge, then cortex recall, then a hardcoded fallback:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (four steps)
(define local (knowledge/of :category \"timezone\"))
(define recalled (if local local (cortex/recall :topic \"user.timezone\")))
(define final (if recalled recalled \"UTC\"))
final
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(or (knowledge/of :category \"timezone\") 
    (cortex/recall :topic \"user.timezone\") 
    \"UTC\")
```

*[needs: knowledge/of, cortex/recall]*

The `or` tries each source in order, short-circuiting on the first success. One form. No `local`. No `recalled`. No `final`.

---

## Speech With Map Over Recalls

Sketch that recalls multiple topics and speaks them as a list:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (three steps)
(define topics '(\"todo.morning\" \"todo.afternoon\"))
(define facts (map (lambda (t) (cortex/recall :topic t)) topics))
(surface :say (string-append \"Tasks: \" (fold string-append \"\" facts)))
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(surface :say 
         (string-append \"Tasks: \" 
                        (fold string-append \"\" 
                              (map (lambda (t) (cortex/recall :topic t)) 
                                   '(\"todo.morning\" \"todo.afternoon\")))))
```

*[needs: cortex/recall, surface :say]*

The map closes inside the fold, the fold closes inside the append, the append closes inside the speech surface. One form. No `topics`. No `facts`.

---

## Nested Conditionals With Wire Fetch

Sketch that checks a local cache, then checks a fallback URL, then escalates:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (four steps)
(define cached (loam/recall :api-data))
(define fetched (if cached cached (fetch \"https://api.example.com/primary\")))
(define fallback (if fetched fetched (fetch \"https://api.example.com/fallback\")))
(if fallback fallback (escalate :reason \"All sources failed.\"))
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(or (loam/recall :api-data) 
    (fetch \"https://api.example.com/primary\") 
    (fetch \"https://api.example.com/fallback\") 
    (escalate :reason \"All sources failed.\"))
```

*[needs: loam/recall, fetch, escalate]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire loam + fetch + escalate -->

The `or` tries each source in order. If all return `#f`, the escalate fires. One form. No `cached`. No `fetched`. No `fallback`.

---

## Map + Store + Retrieve + Fold

Sketch that maps a list, stores each result, retrieves them, and folds:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (four steps)
(define items '(\"a\" \"b\" \"c\"))
(map (lambda (item) (store (string->symbol item) (string-length item))) items)
(define lengths (map (lambda (item) (loam/recall (string->symbol item))) items))
(fold + 0 lengths)
```

Collapse (but note the store/recall gap):

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT (but storage is side-effectful)
(fold + 0 
      (map (lambda (item) 
             (begin 
               (store (string->symbol item) (string-length item)) 
               (loam/recall (string->symbol item)))) 
           '(\"a\" \"b\" \"c\")))
```

*[needs: store, loam/recall]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire store + loam recall; note that begin sequences the side effect -->

This uses `begin` to sequence the store and recall within the map. It's still one top-level form, but the `begin` reveals the sequencing. A purer approach would store once and retrieve later, but that would be two forms.

---

## Knowledge Lookup With Transformation

Sketch that looks up a list of facts and formats them:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (three steps)
(define facts (knowledge/of :category \"planets\"))
(define names (map (lambda (f) (cdr (assoc 'name f))) facts))
(fold (lambda (n acc) (string-append acc n \", \")) \"\" names)
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(fold (lambda (n acc) (string-append acc n \", \")) 
      \"\" 
      (map (lambda (f) (cdr (assoc 'name f))) 
           (knowledge/of :category \"planets\")))
```

*[needs: knowledge/of]*

The knowledge lookup closes inside the map, the map closes inside the fold. One form. No `facts`. No `names`.

---

## Wire Fetch + Guard + Transform + Store

Sketch that fetches data, checks a field, transforms it, and stores it:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (five steps)
(define data (fetch \"https://api.example.com/reading\"))
(define value (assoc 'temperature data))
(define temp (if value (cdr value) 0))
(define celsius (/ (- temp 32) 1.8))
(store :temperature-c celsius)
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(store :temperature-c 
       (/ (- (let ((value (assoc 'temperature (fetch \"https://api.example.com/reading\")))) 
               (if value (cdr value) 0)) 
             32) 
          1.8))
```

*[needs: fetch, store]*

The fetch closes inside the `assoc`, the `assoc` is checked and dereferenced in the `let`, the value is transformed, and the result is stored—all in one form. No `data`. No `value`. No `temp`. No `celsius`.

---

## Speech With Nested Conditionals

Sketch that checks multiple conditions and speaks accordingly:

```scheme
;; SKETCH (four steps)
(define temp (sensor/read :thermometer))
(define time (clock/now))
(define hour (string->number (substring time 11 13)))
(define message (cond ((> temp 30) \"It's hot.\") 
                      ((< hour 12) \"Good morning.\") 
                      (else \"Hello.\")))
(surface :say message)
```

Collapse:

```scheme
;; ONE SHOT
(surface :say 
         (cond ((> (sensor/read :thermometer) 30) \"It's hot.\") 
               ((< (string->number (substring (clock/now) 11 13)) 12) \"Good morning.\") 
               (else \"Hello.\")))
```

*[needs: sensor/read, clock/now, surface :say]*  
<!-- BUILD: wire sensor + clock + speech -->

The sensor read and clock call happen *inside* the `cond`. The `cond` closes inside the speech surface. One form. No `temp`. No `time`. No `hour`. No `message`.

